FreshRSS Greader API checkToken CSRF Protection Bypass
Summary
The FreshRSS Greader API contains a CSRF token validation bypass vulnerability in the checkToken function. The function accepts an empty string or 'x' as valid CSRF tokens for any non-internal user, allowing an attacker with valid API credentials to perform write operations without providing a legitimate CSRF token.
Details
The vulnerability exists in the checkToken function at p/api/greader.php:247-263. This function is called as an anti-CSRF measure for several write operations in the Greader API.
Root Cause:
The checkToken function's validation logic at lines 253-256 has a fatal flaw: for any user that is NOT the internal '_' user (Minz_User::INTERNAL_USER), the function immediately returns true if the provided token ($token) is an empty string ('') or the single character 'x'. This means no actual token verification is performed.
Code Path:
1. Entry point: HTTP POST requests to Greader API endpoints such as /reader/api/0/edit-tag, /reader/api/0/rename-tag, /reader/api/0/disable-tag, /reader/api/0/mark-all-as-read
2. Authentication: The request must first pass authentication via authorizationToUser() (line 1118-1120) which validates the Authorization header
3. The T parameter (token) is extracted from $_POST['T'] and passed to checkToken()
4. checkToken() bypasses validation for empty or 'x' tokens
5. After checkToken returns true, the requested write operation is executed
Trust Boundary Failure:
The function is meant to enforce a trust boundary between a user's session and the API operations by requiring a unique per-session token obtained from /reader/api/0/token. By accepting empty tokens and 'x', this boundary is removed for all non-internal users.
Core vulnerable code path:
// p/api/greader.php:247-263
private static function checkToken(?FreshRSS_UserConfiguration $conf, string $token): bool {
    $user = Minz_User::name();
    if ($user === null || $conf === null || !FreshRSS_Context::hasSystemConf()) {
        self::unauthorized();
    }
    if ($user !== Minz_User::INTERNAL_USER && (
        $token === '' ||
        $token === 'x')) {
        return true;
    }
    if (hash_equals(str_pad(sha1(FreshRSS_Context::systemConf()->salt . $user . $conf->apiPasswordHash), 57, 'Z'), $token)) {
        return true;
    }
    Minz_Log::warning('Invalid POST token: ' . $token, API_LOG);
    self::unauthorized();
}
This is the core validation function. Lines 253-256 introduce a critical bypass: for any user that is not the internal '_' user, if the token parameter is an empty string or 'x', the function returns true immediately without performing any real token validation. The 'TODO: Check security consequences' comment explicitly acknowledges the risk.
// p/api/greader.php:1293-1321
case 'edit-tag':
    $token = is_string($_POST['T'] ?? null) ? trim($_POST['T']) : '';
    self::checkToken(FreshRSS_Context::userConf(), $token);
    $as = self::multiplePosts('a');
    $rs = self::multiplePosts('r');
    $e_ids = self::multiplePosts('i');
    self::editTag($e_ids, $as, $rs);
case 'rename-tag':
    $token = is_string($_POST['T'] ?? null) ? trim($_POST['T']) : '';
    self::checkToken(FreshRSS_Context::userConf(), $token);
case 'disable-tag':
    $token = is_string($_POST['T'] ?? null) ? trim($_POST['T']) : '';
    self::checkToken(FreshRSS_Context::userConf(), $token);
case 'mark-all-as-read':
    $token = is_string($_POST['T'] ?? null) ? trim($_POST['T']) : '';
    self::checkToken(FreshRSS_Context::userConf(), $token);
These are the four API endpoint handlers that invoke checkToken() as CSRF protection. Each one extracts the T parameter from the POST request and passes it to checkToken(). Due to the vulnerability in checkToken(), all these write operations can be performed without a valid CSRF token by sending an empty T parameter.
POC
Preconditions: The attacker must have valid Greader API credentials. The target FreshRSS must have API enabled.
Proof of Concept:
1. Obtain API auth: POST /api/greader.php/accounts/ClientLogin with Body: Email=target_user&Passwd=api_password
2. Send write request with empty T: POST /api/greader.php/reader/api/0/edit-tag
Authorization: GoogleLogin auth=target_user/TOKEN_VALUE
Body: T=&i=entry_id&a=user/-/state/com.google/read
3. Expected result: HTTP 200 OK despite empty CSRF token, the entry is marked as read.
Impact
An attacker with valid API credentials can mark any entry as read/unread, star/unstar entries, rename/disable categories, and mark entire feeds as read, all without obtaining a proper CSRF token.
Remediation
Remove the compatibility bypass logic in checkToken() that accepts empty strings and 'x' as valid tokens. The function should enforce proper token validation for ALL users except the internal '_' user. Delete or comment out lines 253-256 in p/api/greader.php.
Disclosure Notes
The code contains a 'TODO: Check security consequences' comment at line 253. Vulnerability identified through static code analysis. Dynamic verification recommended. Affected version: FreshRSS 1.29.1.
